         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0237">
               <p>The son of a gardener-turned-soldier, Bradburn was converted in <date when="1769"
                     >1769</date>, became a local preacher in <date when="1773">1773</date>, and an
                     <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg> the following year. He was an eloquent
                  preacher, writer, and protagonist for Methodism against establishment intolerance.
                  He was also a frequent correspondent of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>John Wesley</persName>. See <hi
                     rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 129; <hi rend="italic">Minutes</hi> (post-Wesley, <date
                     when="1816">1816</date>), 4:196; Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>,
                  40; and <hi rend="italic">Wesley&apos;s Chapel Magazine</hi> 8 (<date
                     when="1938-03">March 1938</date>), 17ff.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
